the June 2000 Harare Democratic Conference where the National Constitutional Assembly (NCA) proposed reform of the country’s 1980 Lancaster House Constitution and subsequently organised a mass protest action three days later in Harare that ultimately forced Government to scrap the proposal for constitutional reform. 

After the exciting progress in constitutional development in Namibia, Swaziland, and South Africa, the people of Zimbabwe began to hold out great hope that similar reform would be adopted in Zimbabwe. Zimbabwe then lacked a highly visible and nationally meaningful pro-democracy movement to drive this reform process forward. 

The incredible move by the NCA back in June 2000 marked the fulfilment of democratic ruling party rhetoric and re-enforced emphasis on the unity of the Ndebele and Shona struggle for emancipation from colonial imposition to the post colonial embryonic government. Prior to the June 2000 events, the country had 70 political parties. The parties became registered after the country’s independence from Britain in 1980 but had remained dormant politically. The partners, which formed the MDC a coalition of parties, drew their support from this multiplicity of parties. The movement, formed in March 1999 represented the fusion of several opposition political parties and it was led by Morgan Tsvangirai. From the name chosen by the movement, opposition politicians and the wider civil society made capital from the declaration that the impact of land reform policy had been negative to Zimbabwe’s economy.
